<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The genus 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Zornia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Zornia" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Zornia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises 80 species mainly distributed in tropical regions of the world (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.12705/624.35" author="Fortuna-Perez, AP" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="723 - 732" refId="B56" refString="Fortuna-Perez, AP, da Silva, MJ, de Queiroz, LP, Lewis, GP, Simoes, AO, de Azevedo Tozzi, AMG, Sarkinen, T, de Souza, AP, 2013. Phylogeny and biogeography of the genus Zornia (Leguminosae: Papilionoideae: Dalbergieae). Taxon 62: 723 - 732, DOI: https://doi.org/10.12705/624.35" title="Phylogeny and biogeography of the genus Zornia (Leguminosae: Papilionoideae: Dalbergieae)." url="https://doi.org/10.12705/624.35" volume="62" year="2013">Fortuna-Perez et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). No species of 
<taxonomicName class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Cercospora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are currently known on hosts belonging to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Zornia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Zornia" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Zornia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Farr, DF" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Genetics and Cytology" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" publicationUrl="https://nt.ars-grin.gov/fungaldatabases/" refId="B54" refString="Farr, DF, Rossman, AY, 2021. Fungal Databases, U.S. National Fungus Collections, ARS, USDA. https://nt.ars-grin.gov/fungaldatabases/" title="Fungal Databases, U. S. National Fungus Collections, ARS, USDA." url="https://nt.ars-grin.gov/fungaldatabases/" year="2021">Farr and Rossman 2021</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Deighton" authorityYear="1976" baseAuthorityName="J.M. Yen &amp; Gilles" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Fabaceae" genus="Pseudocercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Pseudocercospora zorniae" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="zorniae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Pseudocercospora zorniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(J.M. Yen &amp; Gilles) Deighton (≡ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J.M.Yen &amp; Gilles" authorityYear="1970" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora zorniae" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="zorniae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Cercospora zorniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
J.M. Yen &amp; Gilles) is the only known species of cercosporoid fungi infecting species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Zornia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Zornia" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Zornia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
In the multi-gene phylogeny (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. The Bayesian phylogenetic tree inferred from DNA sequence data from the multigene alignment (SSU rDNA, LSU rDNA, ITS and tef 1) of cercosporoid species. Nodes receiving Bayesian PP ≥ 0.94 or MLBS ≥ 70 % are considered as strongly supported and are indicated by thickened branches. Names of newly described species are written in bold and red. Species newly reported for Benin are indicated by green letters. Names of host plants are written with blue letters." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.81.67850.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/556600" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">1</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora zorniicola" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="zorniicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Cercospora zorniicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grouped closely, but with poor support, with isolates of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cooke" authorityYear="1883" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora citrullina" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="citrullina">Cercospora cf. citrullina</taxonomicName>
(MUCC 576) on 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Citrullus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Citrullus lanatus" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="lanatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Citrullus lanatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Thunb.) Matsum. &amp; Nakai (
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Citrullus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Cucurbitaceae</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. kikuchii" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kikuchii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. kikuchii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Glycine" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Glycine max" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="max">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Glycine max</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Phaseolus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Phaseolus" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Phaseolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp., 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Fabaceae" genus="Cyamopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cyamopsis tetragonoloba" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="tetragonoloba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Cyamopsis tetragonoloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) Taub., 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Vigna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vigna" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Vigna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Vigna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
hosts (
<bibRefCitation author="Mulder, JL" journalOrPublisher="IMA Fungus" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B97" refString="Mulder, JL, Holliday, P, 1975. Cercospora canescens. CMI descriptions of phytopathogenic fungi and bacteria 462." title="Cercospora canescens. CMI descriptions of phytopathogenic fungi and bacteria 462." year="1975">Mulder and Holliday 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim0012" author="Groenewald, JZ" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="115 - 170" refId="B64" refString="Groenewald, JZ, Nakashima, C, Nishikawa, J, Shin, H-D, Park, J-H, Jama, AN, Groenewald, M, Braun, U, Crous, PW, 2013. Species concepts in Cercospora: spotting the weeds among the roses. Studies in Mycology 75: 115 - 170, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3114/sim0012" title="Species concepts in Cercospora: spotting the weeds among the roses." url="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim0012" volume="75" year="2013">Groenewald et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). However, morphologically, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. zorniicola" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zorniicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. zorniicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly distinct from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. citrullina" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="citrullina">C. cf. citrullina</taxonomicName>
by external hyphae, unbranched, darker and longer conidiophores [(15-)24.5-134(-158) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
] and somewhat longer conidia [(15-)27.5-182.5(-200) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
], while 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. citrullina" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="citrullina">C. cf. citrullina</taxonomicName>
has pale to pale brown and short conidiophores (50-86 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and shorter conidia (40-130 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim0012" author="Groenewald, JZ" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="115 - 170" refId="B64" refString="Groenewald, JZ, Nakashima, C, Nishikawa, J, Shin, H-D, Park, J-H, Jama, AN, Groenewald, M, Braun, U, Crous, PW, 2013. Species concepts in Cercospora: spotting the weeds among the roses. Studies in Mycology 75: 115 - 170, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3114/sim0012" title="Species concepts in Cercospora: spotting the weeds among the roses." url="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim0012" volume="75" year="2013">Groenewald et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. zorniicola" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zorniicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. zorniicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. kikuchii" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kikuchii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. kikuchii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having external hyphae, darker and shorter conidiophores [(15-)24.5-134(-158) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
] and shorter conidia [(15-)27.5-182.5(-200) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
], while 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. kikuchii" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kikuchii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. kikuchii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has paler and longer conidiophores (45-200 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and above all, much longer conidia (50-375 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) with numerous indistinct septa (
<bibRefCitation author="Mulder, JL" journalOrPublisher="IMA Fungus" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B97" refString="Mulder, JL, Holliday, P, 1975. Cercospora canescens. CMI descriptions of phytopathogenic fungi and bacteria 462." title="Cercospora canescens. CMI descriptions of phytopathogenic fungi and bacteria 462." year="1975">Mulder and Holliday 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hsieh, WH" journalOrPublisher="Maw Chang Book Co, Taipei" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B75" refString="Hsieh, WH, Goh, TK, 1990. Cercospora and Similar Fungi from Taiwan. Maw Chang Book Co, Taipei" title="Cercospora and Similar Fungi from Taiwan." year="1990">Hsieh and Goh 1990</bibRefCitation>
). In the phylogeny based on 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">tef1</emphasis>
molecular sequence data, it is not possible to distinguish 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. zorniicola" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zorniicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. zorniicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other 
<taxonomicName class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Cercospora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. (see Suppl. material 4).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
Based on a MegaBLAST search in the NCBI GenBank nucleotide database using the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">tef1</emphasis>
sequence data of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. zorniicola" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zorniicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. zorniicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the closest matches were 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ellis &amp; G. Martin, Am. Nat. 16 (12): 1003" authorityYear="1882" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora canescens" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="canescens">Cercospora aff. canescens</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Dioscoreaceae" genus="Dioscorea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dioscorea rotundata" order="Liliiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="rotundata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Dioscorea rotundata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Poir. (
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Dioscoreaceae" genus="Dioscorea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Liliiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Dioscoreaceae</taxonomicName>
) from Ghana (GenBank JX143316; Identities 294 / 300, i.e., 98%), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W.W. Ray" authorityYear="1941" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora coreopsidis" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="coreopsidis">Cercospora cf. coreopsidis</taxonomicName>
W.W. Ray on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Coreopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Coreopsis lanceolata" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanceolata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Coreopsis lanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Coreopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
) form South Korea (GenBank JX143344; Identities 293 / 300, i.e., 97%) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ellis &amp; Everhart" authorityYear="1893" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora nicotianae" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="nicotianae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Cercospora nicotianae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Nicotiana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Nicotiana tabacum" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="tabacum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Nicotiana tabacum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Nicotiana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Solanaceae</taxonomicName>
) from China (GenBank MK881748; Identities 292 / 300, i.e., 97%). This species is proposed to be new to science based on a distinct combination of morphological characteristics and because no other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Cercospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cercospora" order="Mycosphaerellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Cercospora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known on a species of this host genus.
</paragraph>
